00:25:57.130 --> 00:25:58.670
Where is your husband?

508
00:26:05.370 --> 00:26:07.870
If I do dream, would allmy wealth would wake me.

509
00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:10.530
If I do wake, some planetstrike me down,

510
00:26:10.530 --> 00:26:12.700
that I may slumber ineternal sleep.

511
00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:14.600
Speak, gentle niece.

512
00:26:16.930 --> 00:26:19.870
What stern, ungentle hand

513
00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:24.370
hath lopped and hewed andmade thy body bare

514
00:26:24.370 --> 00:26:27.530
of her two branches, thosesweet ornaments,

515
00:26:27.530 --> 00:26:31.030
whose circling shadowskings have sought to sleepin?

516
00:26:32.500 --> 00:26:34.230
Why dost not speak to me?

517
00:26:36.330 --> 00:26:40.300
Alas, a crimson river ofwarm blood,

518
00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:42.600
like to a bubblingfountain stirred withwind,

519
00:26:42.600 --> 00:26:45.030
doth rise and fall betweenthy rosed lips,

520
00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:47.630
coming and going with thyhoney breath.

521
00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:52.470
But sure, some Tereus hathdeflowered thee

522
00:26:52.470 --> 00:26:55.630
and, lest thou should'stdetect him, cut thytongue.

523
00:26:55.630 --> 00:27:00.230
Ah, now thou turn'st awaythy face for shame.

524
00:27:00.230 --> 00:27:04.200
And notwithstanding allthis loss of blood

525
00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:08.600
as from a conduit withthree issuing spouts

526
00:27:08.600 --> 00:27:11.570
yet do thy cheeks look redas Titan's face

527
00:27:11.570 --> 00:27:14.130
blushing to be encounteredwith a cloud.

528
00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:18.130
Shall I speak for thee?

529
00:27:18.130 --> 00:27:19.670
Shall I say 'tis so?

530
00:27:22.170 --> 00:27:26.930
O, that I knew thy heartand knew the beast,

531
00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:29.670
that I might rail at himto ease my mind.

532
00:27:29.670 --> 00:27:31.730
Sorrow concealed, like anoven stopped,

533
00:27:31.730 --> 00:27:34.700
doth burn the heart tocinders where it is.

534
00:27:34.700 --> 00:27:37.530
Fair Philomel, why she butlost her tongue

535
00:27:37.530 --> 00:27:39.870
and in a tedious samplersewed her mind.

536
00:27:39.870 --> 00:27:42.830
But, gentle niece, thatmean is cut from thee.

537
00:27:44.470 --> 00:27:47.370
A craftier Tereus, cousin,hast thou met,

538
00:27:47.370 --> 00:27:49.730
for he hath cut thy prettyfingers off

539
00:27:49.730 --> 00:27:51.830
that could have bettersewed than Philomel.

540
00:27:53.170 --> 00:27:55.900
O, had the monster seenthose lily hands

541
00:27:55.900 --> 00:27:58.730
tremble like aspen leavesupon the lute

542
00:27:58.730 --> 00:28:01.430
and make the silkenstrings delight to kissthem,

543
00:28:01.430 --> 00:28:04.400
he would not then havetouched them for his life.

544
00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:08.800
Or had he heard theheavenly harmony

545
00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:11.270
which that sweet, sweettongue hath made,

546
00:28:11.270 --> 00:28:14.000
he would have dropped hisknife and fell asleep

547
00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.630
as Cerberus at theThracian poet's feet.

548
00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:25.030
Come, let us go and makethy father blind,

549
00:28:25.030 --> 00:28:29.130
for such a sight willblind a father's eye.

550
00:28:30.230 --> 00:28:32.900
When one hour's storm willdrown the fragrant meads,

551
00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:36.700
what will whole months oftears thy father's eyes?

552
00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:44.130
Do not draw back, for wewill mourn with thee.

553
00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:51.630
O, could our mourning easethy misery.

